{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}
{% set nav = 'land' %}

{% block title %}The land and its resources · Robinson Huron Treaty{% endblock %}
{% block description %}The Robinson Huron Treaty is about the land and what it produces: decisions on the territory, energy and resource projects, consultation, and the environment, and how they reach members across the 21 nations.{% endblock %}
{% block og_description %}The land section: energy and resource projects, consultation, and the environment across the Robinson Huron Treaty territory, and how members can understand and ask about them.{% endblock %}

{% block hero %}
<section class="hero">
  <div class="wrap wrap--wide">
    <p class="eyebrow">Across the territory</p>
    <h1>The land and its resources.</h1>
    <p class="lead">The Robinson Huron Treaty is about the land and what it produces. Decisions made on the territory, energy and resource projects, consultation, and the environment, reach every member, not only the community where they happen. This section helps members across the 21 nations understand those decisions and ask about them, the same way the shared standard helps with the money. Sources are linked throughout. We work from facts and we ask questions.</p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <h2>Projects</h2>
  <ul class="community-grid">
    <li><a class="community-card" href="/land/massey-solar-project">
      <p class="name">Massey Solar Project</p>
      <p class="pillar-desc">A sourced guide to a utility-scale solar project proposed on the territory: what is settled, what is still being decided, and how to take part in the review.</p>
    </a></li>
  </ul>
  <p class="muted">More projects as members raise them. As resource and energy decisions come up across the treaty, the Circle gathers the public record and the questions members can ask.</p>

  <h2>Territory and member safety</h2>
  <p>The land is also about the people on it. This is a neutral, sourced note on groups organizing in or visiting the territory in ways that affect members. It relays what credible public bodies have documented, with a source for every claim, and frames the member-facing part as questions rather than alarm.</p>
  <ul class="community-grid">
    <li><a class="community-card" href="/land/territory-and-safety">
      <p class="name">Territory and member safety</p>
      <p class="pillar-desc">What credible public bodies have documented about groups active in the territory. First entry: Second Sons Canada.</p>
    </a></li>
  </ul>
{% endblock %}
